<paragraph blockId="161.[2057,2650,2826,3244]" lastBlockId="161.[1445,2650,3255,3480]" pageId="161" pageNumber="764">
<subSubSection pageId="161" pageNumber="764" type="discussion">
Although previously treated as a subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Smuts" baseAuthorityYear="1832" box="[2160,2347,2983,3008]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Grammomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="161" pageNumber="764" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dolichurus">G. dolichurus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1907" box="[2382,2459,2983,3008]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Thamnomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="161" pageNumber="764" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dryas">G.dryas</taxonomicName>
was later recognized as a good species. Monotypic.
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="161" pageNumber="764" type="distribution">
<caption inLine="true" pageId="161" pageNumber="764" startId="161.[2057,2225,3049,3087]" targetBox="[1443,2034,2831,3234]" targetPageId="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2057,2229,3049,3087]" pageId="161" pageNumber="764">Distribution.</emphasis>
Restricted to elevations above 1000 m within the Albertine Rift Mts.
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="161" pageNumber="764" type="description">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2057,2341,3137,3166]" pageId="161" pageNumber="764">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 100-130 mm, tail 142-177 mm, car 15-21 mm, hindfoot 22-28 mm; weight 30-59 g. Fur of the Albertine Rift Thicket Rat is tawny brown above, becoming brighter orange brown on rump, with sharply demarcated pure white belly bordered by thin orange line. Tail is very long (160% of head-body length), semi-prehensile, tufted, and dark brown. Feet are pale buff, with four digits on forefoot and five on relatively short hindfoot, fifth digit longer and semi-opposable. Females have 0+2 = 2 pairs of nipples.
</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
<subSubSection pageId="162" pageNumber="765" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="162.[88,1295,265,687]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[89,200,298,332]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">Habitat.</emphasis>
Secondary forest and scrubby habitats, including banana plantations and garden shrubs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[90,1041,381,410]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="162.[88,1295,265,687]" box="[90,1041,381,410]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[90,351,381,410]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
Diet includes vegetable matter and ground nuts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[90,1142,420,449]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="162.[88,1295,265,687]" box="[90,1142,420,449]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[90,224,420,449]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">Breeding.</emphasis>
There is no well-defined breeding season. Embryos number 1-6.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="162" pageNumber="765" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="162.[88,1295,265,687]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[88,323,460,489]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Albertine Rift Thicket Rat are nocturnal and arboreal, although they are often caught on the ground.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[90,1029,535,569]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="162.[88,1295,265,687]" box="[90,1029,535,569]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[90,790,535,569]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[90,1180,574,608]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="162.[88,1295,265,687]" box="[90,1180,574,608]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[90,439,574,608]" pageId="162" pageNumber="765">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Near Threatened on The IUCN Red Lust.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
